0180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="seasiaz"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Southeast Asia</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="re:singp"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet><CSet fid="ns"><Code value="gtrans"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Transport</CodeD><CodeI org="categoriser" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="es-EnglishNS_en_20180316142643"/><CodeA name="es_score" value="142"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gcat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Political/General News</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gtrans"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Home</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Citymapper gives alternatives when MRT fails</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>At a loss when trains break down? Transport app provider Citymapper has introduced a feature in its wayfinding platform which will not only alert commuters to a rail glitch as soon as it happens, but will also suggest alternative routes.</Para><Para>For instance, if there is a breakdown along the Downtown Line between Beauty World and Bugis stations, the app will suggest taking bus service 170.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Citymapper has rail alerts in cities such such as Hong Kong, London, Paris and New York City. In Hong Kong, it claims it is the only app which offers the alternative route option when incidents occur on the MTR.</Para><Para>In Singapore, it is believed to be the first to offer this option.</Para><Para>The free app taps into information available on the Land Transport Authority's Datamall. The moment there is a disruption, the app will have five suggested alternative routes.</Para><Para>If a user has a favourite MRT line, he can also choose to be notified when a disruption occurs on that line.</Para><Para>Ms Patsy Ho, Citymapper's city operations manager for Asia, said: "We can launch this feature when there is enough data provided, preferably from an official source that has first-hand information about the metro status.</Para><Para>"The data also needs to be machine-readable so that robots can handle it in real time. In Singapore, the hard work is in phrasing the alert messages so that we, and thus the users, can quickly understand which part of the MRT line is affected."</Para><Para>Commuters here often complain about not having adequate and timely information on what they should do after a rail breakdown, despite efforts by operators to offer stop-gap measures such as bus bridging services and free regular buses.</Para><Para>Commenting on the app, Singapore University of Social Sciences senior lecturer and transport economist Walter Theseira said "the real value-add is in the rerouting advice", but said "some testing is required to determine if the advice the app gives on rerouting is actually superior to following the recovery plans of the rail operator".</Para><Para>"For example, we don't know if bus bridging services are faster, or if taking an alternative route is faster - as when people divert themselves to alternative routes, those routes get congested as well, which may impact travel times," Dr Theseira added.</Para><Para>"I am not sure if the rerouting algorithm they have deployed takes such effects into account.</Para><Para>"Probably the greatest benefit will be to commuters who haven't yet entered the area of disruption, and who can still reroute effectively by avoiding the disruption zone entirely."</Para><Para>Commuter Jeff Chew said he found the Citymapper app somewhat "unwieldy" even if "it has a lot of features".</Para><Para>The 80-year-old retiree, who uses public transport regularly, said: "It's a good idea, and it is quite promising. But it is hard to know how useful it is unless there is a real breakdown."</Para><Para>He added that it is also not as "intuitive" as another travel app - gothere.sg - he uses. "But of course, that does not have breakdown contingency," he noted.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Christopher Tan </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">Citymapper will not only alert commuters to a rail glitch as soon as it happens, but it also suggests alternative routes. The free app taps into information available on the Land Transport Authority's Datamall. </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

